<p>play the manly and honourable part, whether on the battlefield ora elsewhere, and that whatever he did, the honour of his parents' name was safe in his hands. There was a great charm about him."</p>
<p>Did you see Mrs. Curlewis's verses in this morning's Herald?</p>
<p>Arthur very often worshiped at St Stephen's with his brothers. The last time he was there was when he came down from Liverpool to attend the memorial service for his old chief, Normand MacLaurin.</p>
<p>Yours very sincerely,</p>
<p>A very old friend writes:</p>
<p>"But you and his poor mother, who knew his dreadful risk and faced it all along, will yet find some consolation in the thought that your brave boy died for France &ndash; yes, for unconquerable France, from whose soil sprang the dear old lady who was our good angel in days that are no more."</p>
